item.paragraph: Only the most recent of 6 results within the time period is included.

td.paragraph: ASANTE SPEECHQ
IMPRESSION: Benign
BI-RADS CATEGORY: 2- Benign finding(s).
A.A certain low percentage of breast carcinomas are occult to imaging, and a negative report should not necessarily preclude biopsy of a clinically suspicious lesion.
B.Up to 15% of palpable breast carcinomas are not visible on mammogram.
C.American Cancer Society recommendations for early breast cancer detection:
1.Women age 40 and older should have a screening mammogram every year and should continue to do so for as long as they are in good health.

2.Women in their 20s and 30s should have a clinical breast exam(CBE) as part of a periodic (regular) health exam by a health professional, at least every 3 years. After age 40, women should have a breast exam by a health professional every year.

3.Breast self exam (BSE) is an option for women starting in their 20s. Women should be told about the benefits and limitations of BSE. Women should report any breast changes to their health professional right away.

4.Women at high risk (greater than 20% lifetime risk) should get an MRI and a mammogram every year. Women at moderately increased risk (15% to 20% lifetime risk) should talk with their doctors about the benefits and limitations of adding MRI screening
to their yearly mammogram. Yearly MRI screening is not recommended for women whose lifetime risk of breast cancer is less than 15%.
MAMMO SCREENING BILATERAL DIGITAL W CAD 4/3/2015 08:48:10
CLINICAL INDICATION: Screening.
TECHNIQUE: Images of both breasts were obtained in mediolateral oblique (MLO) and craniocaudal (CC) projections.This exam is reviewed with the benefit of computer-aided detection (CAD) software.

FINDINGS: The breast parenchymal pattern is scattered fibroglandular.There a few benign-appearing calcifications bilaterally which are stable. No evidence of focal dominant mass, cluster of pleomorphic microcalcifications, skin thickening or nipple
retraction of a suspicious nature.

item.caption: CT abdomen w wo pelvis w contrast (12/31/2008 7:56 PM)

td.paragraph: ASANTE NOVIUS RIS
IMPRESSION:1. Inflammatory changes within the right lower quadrant.
Distended, air-filled tubular structure may represent an enlarged appendix.
A definitive mass in the right lower quadrant is not identified. The
ascending colon is fluid filled and distended as well as the small bowel
diffusely, consistent with small bowel ileus. Focal diverticulitis cannot be
excluded. There is no free air or a drainable fluid collection present.
There are a few mildly prominent lymph nodes within the right lower quadrant.
2. Small hiatal hernia.
3. No obstructive uropathy.
Recommend either Gastrografin barium enema with repeat study to evaluate for
opacification of the appendix and distal ileum.A call report of these
findings was given to Dr. O'Neal on December 31, 2008, at 8:45 p.m.

RCT 2212 - CT ABDOMEN W/WO CON-PELVIS W/CON - Dec 31 2008
CLINICAL HISTORY:Abdominal pain for 2 days with vomiting.Evaluate for
appendicitis.
COMPARISON:No prior exams.
TECHNIQUE:Approximately 85 mL Omnipaque 350 given intravenously without
complication.Oral contrast was not given.Precontrast, postcontrast and
delayed phase axial imaging through the abdomen and pelvis was performed.
Sagittal and coronal reconstructed images were generated.
FINDINGS:The lung bases and partly visualized heart are unremarkable.
There is a small hiatal hernia present.The distal thoracic aorta and
abdominal aorta demonstrate no evidence of aneurysm or dissection.The
liver demonstrates a hypodense liver lesion seen in the left liver segment
near the diaphragmatic dome, image 9, series 4, measuring 13.5 mm, and
appears to represent a simple cyst. The remainder of the liver appears
unremarkable. The gallbladder, spleen, bilateral adrenal glands, and
pancreas appear unremarkable.The bilateral kidneys are unremarkable.
There is no obstructive uropathy.The unopacified gastrointestinal tract
demonstrates numerous dilated fluid-filled loops of small bowel, also
dilated fluid-filled ascending colon extending retrograde to the mid distal
transverse colon. The sigmoid colon is primarily decompressed. There is
high-density contrast material lying within the dependent position of a
distended cecum and ascending colon. There appears to be a rather
heterogeneous though prominent soft tissue-type mass, which may be a
distended appendix, seen in the right lower quadrant. This is not well
visualized on this unenhanced exam. There may be a few mildlyprominent
lymph nodes within the right lower quadrant. Otherwise, there is no
significant abdominal or pelvic adenopathy. There is a prominent,
air-filled, tubular structure seen in the right lower quadrant, which could
also represent a very distended, air-and-debris-filled apparent appendix,
which is markedly distended, measuring 13.5 mm in maximum dimension, seen on
image 53, series 4. The uterus appears unremarkable. The bilateral ovaries
are poorly visualized and may be atrophied. The left ovary may be present,
measuring 16.9 mm in diameter.There are several phleboliths in the pelvis.
The osseous structures demonstrate no evidence for a fracture, lytic or
blastic bony destructive lesions.

td.paragraph: ASANTE NOVIUS RIS
IMPRESSION:Negative mammogram.
BI-RADS Category 1:Negative.
A. A negative x-ray report should not delay biopsy if a dominant or
clinically suspicious mass is present.
B. Up to 15% of palpable breast cancers are not visible on mammograms.
C. Examinations which employe computer-assisted diagnosis (CAD) use
ImageChecker version 3.2 by R2 Technology.
D. The American Cancer Society guidelines for the detection of breast
cancer in asymptomatic women are as follows:
1. Women 20 years of age and older should perform breast
self-examination every month.
2. Women 20-40 years of age should have a physical exam of the breasts
every 3 years, and women over 40 should have a physical examination of the
breasts every year.
3. Women over 40 years of age should have a mammogram and clinical exam
every year.
